I have a really hard time reading this test case. The test intent is unclear for a number of reasons:
* The main assertion (that is called "CHECKRoundtrip") relies on member variables of a fixture.
* The checked roundtrip is not really a roundtrip. A roundtrip would be to insert the data and retrieve it.
* The test looks like it is about testing `Int64Builder` and `Int16Builder` because of all the extra asserts
* The terms `array` and `compressed_array` are not saying much. One could be called `input_64_bits` and the other `expected_output_16_bits`

The test would be much easier to read as this:
```
TEST_F(ArrowResultSetTest, ConversionCompressedInteger)
{
    auto input_data = make_64bit_integers_table(1024);
    auto base_result_set = make_prepared_results(input_data, {{"int_column", turbodbc::type_code::integer, size_unimportant, true}}, input_data);
    
    auto expected = make_16bit_integers_table(1024);
    assert_fetched_result(expected, base_result_set, strings_as_strings, compressed_integers);
}
```
(with adequately designed helper functions).

This layout would not require the use of a test fixture, makes important assertions explicit, and hides setup complexity (and setup assertions) in helper functions so the end result is easier to read.

